      "rationale": "Systematic grid convergence study performed across three mesh refinement levels (4.2M, 12.1M, 28.7M cells) following ASME V&V 20 GCI methodology. GCI for NIH prediction: 6.8% on finest mesh pair. Explicitly noted that confidence in near-wall hemolysis region is low due to high shear gradients; GCI there reaches 14.2%. This limitation is documented. The volume-averaged NIH GCI of 6.8% satisfies Gradation 3 threshold for MRL 5. Wide uncertainty acknowledged in rationale."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-conditions-mrl5-gradation3",
      "rationale": "Bench test conditions (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid temperature, hematocrit) are documented with calibrated instrumentation traceable to NIST standards. Uncertainty in flow rate measurement: ±1.8% (k=2). Hematocrit controlled at 33±1%. All 5 operating points replicated in triplicate. Test conditions match COU operating envelope. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/output-comparison-mrl5-gradation3",
      "rationale": "NIH predictions compared against bench measurements at all 5 operating points. Predictions fall within ±35% of measured values; this wide spread is explicitly documented as arising from hemolysis model-form uncertainty (power-law exponent variability). Despite the wide band, all 5 predictions are directionally correct and the 90th-percentile Monte Carlo bound remains below the clinical threshold. The team rates confidence in output comparison as LOW-MODERATE but accepts Gradation 3 given the conservative threshold margin of 22%."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/qoi-relevance-mrl5-gradation3",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI (NIH, g/100L) is the direct clinical metric used in FDA guidance for VAD hemolysis evaluation. Secondary QoIs (shear stress distribution, residence time) are physically linked to NIH and verified against PIV data. QoI relevance to COU is high. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/validation-relevance-mrl5-gradation3",
      "rationale": "Validation activities were conducted on the identical FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry at the same 5 COU operating points. Fluid (bovine blood, 33% hematocrit) matches COU specification. Boundary conditions replicate clinical VAD operating range. No extrapolation from surrogate geometry required. Gradation 3 achieved with high confidence in this factor specifically."
    },
    {
